raw_response:
[
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "AUSTRIA",
    "content": "Austria — this is France. We have little time for niceties. The storyworld artifact I have (russia_to_austria_grudger) indicates a 60% chance you will face or choose aggression next phase and only a 40% chance of restraint; its confidence is 0.6. Forecast implication: you should expect that Russia’s messaging (and the memory of past slights framed as GRUDGER) will make a punitive or preemptive move more likely, raising the odds of a Balkan flare-up. I offer a simple bargain: keep your forces focused on holding Vienna and Trieste, avoid a southward gamble into Russian zones, and I will refrain from opportunistic moves into Tyrolia or supporting Russian pushes that would expose your home centers. In short: you secure your rear with modest caution (probability of open conflict reduced by my restraint), and I secure my eastern flank without overextending toward the Channel. If you disagree, I will interpret inaction as willingness to gamble and respond accordingly. Reply with a clear military posture so we may coordinate."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ENGLAND",
    "content": "England — France speaking plainly. You sit atop a sea empire and I sit on the knife-edge. Your 10 SCs make you comfortable; my 3 make me dangerous if cornered. Forecast implication from the same artifact: Austria is likelier than not (≈60%) to choose an aggressive Balkan option, which increases the chance of a wider eastern conflagration. That benefits neither of us if it draws Russia into a southern war and the Ottoman into opportunism. Proposal: we agree to a west-oriented non-aggression understanding this turn. I will not contest your hold on Belgium or the Channel if you publicly avoid moves targeting Brest or the Atlantic approaches for S1915M. In exchange, I ask for diplomatic silence (no surprise claims against my southern coasts) and for you to pressure any of your neighbors considering opportunistic fleets toward my shores. This buys us both time — you keep naval dominance, I keep continental breathing room. If you accept, I will move to shore up my immediate borders (Breton/Paris coordination) rather than hazard an ill-advised strike at England. Answer yes/no and, if yes, signal to Germany and Italy that your aim is stability in the west."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "GERMANY",
    "content": "Germany — France here. I will be frank: I want security, not annihilation, and I prefer a balance that leaves Germany strong but checked. The forecast artifact signals a 60% chance Austria turns aggressive in the Balkans; that risk could spill west if Russia counters hard. For my part I will not mass against you in the north provided you show restraint toward my eastern approaches (Burgundy/Bur and Picardy). Tactical suggestion: maintain your army posture in Munich/Berlin for now and avoid an immediate push into Burgundy; do so and I will not attempt an early gamble for Belgian or English centers. If you instead back Austria’s aggression and let the Balkans erupt, expect me to take advantage of German distraction with calibrated moves into neutral Burgundy/Picardy to secure French survival. Make the safe choice and we can negotiate clear lines of interest — I prefer cooperation at ~70% probability of keeping the Channel quiet if you commit to no northern expansion this turn."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "RUSSIA",
    "content": "Russia — France speaking as a friend in a dangerous neighborhood. I share the artifact you sent concerning Austria: it assigns a 0.6 probability that Austria will behave aggressively next phase. Forecast implication: this raises the chance that Austria’s moves will provoke Ottoman/Russian responses and widen the Balkan fighting. I propose you use that leverage now to persuade Austria toward restraint — remind them that a southern push has a >50% chance of creating long-term grudges and drawing in France if western fronts destabilize. I will not join any sudden Austrian smash into the Balkans, but I will exploit any overreach that threatens my home centers. If you can secure Austria’s promise to avoid reckless southern offensives, I will quietly coordinate to keep pressure off your western flank and avoid tempting England into a full naval-assisted intervention. Tell me your read and whether you can move to de-escalate Vienna."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: a short, clear note from France. My immediate goal is survival and a stable western front. I am prepared to bargain: I will not challenge English sea dominance or seek sudden gains in the Channel if Germany and Austria avoid reckless southern or western gambits this turn. The storyworld forecast (russia_to_austria_grudger) implies Austria has a 60% chance of choosing aggression next phase; that raises systemic risk. If Austria restrains, the probability of a multi-front war drops meaningfully and we can arrange non-aggression pacts that preserve your gains while stabilizing the map. My intent is to lock a defensible status quo — Par/Bre/Mar held — while using diplomacy to deter opportunism. Respond with commitments or I will act to secure Burgundy/Picardy and Gascony as necessary to ensure France’s survival."
  }
]

[
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: the map is clear — England will preserve sea-lanes and prevent any single continental power dominating northwestern Europe. I will not precipitate continental collapse, but I will act firmly where my naval and coastal armies secure the Channel and North Sea. Expect me to hold Belgium, Holland and the Danish-Swedish bridge to keep maritime access open. I prefer flexible, issue-by-issue alliances rather than exclusive commitments; if a partner threatens the balance, I will recalibrate. Forecast implication: an intelligence artifact indicates a 60% chance that France may act aggressively next phase, so I will treat French moves toward our shared coastal zones as 60% likely to be offensive and plan accordingly. Practical note: I can defend the Channel and project pressure into Picardy and the Low Countries with minimal risk if allies coordinate — ask before you contest Holland/Belgium so we avoid accidental clashes."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "FRANCE",
    "content": "Paris — candidly: your position is perilous and I prefer you as a cooperative partner rather than a desperate foe. I will hold Belgium and the Channel; my fleets and coastal armies make raids or reinforcements to Picardy and the Channel coast straightforward. However, intelligence (confidence 0.6) flags a 60% probability you might move aggressively next phase; that influences my posture and reduces my tolerance for surprises. If you commit to restraint in the west (no sudden moves into BEL/PIC/HOL), I will refrain from contesting Marseille’s approaches and can offer limited support against local threats in the south. Suggestion: publicly declare you will avoid Picardy and Holland this move and coordinate with me on any operations in the south — that lowers the chance of miscalculation and keeps supply lanes safe."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "GERMANY",
    "content": "Berlin — England intends to keep the North Sea and Channel secure, and to prefer balance over continental hegemony. I note Germany is a natural counterweight to any French overreach. I will not provoke you so long as you avoid sudden naval thrusts into the Channel nor expand unchecked into the Low Countries; our naval forecast shows that coordinated German moves into Belgium or Holland would create a 70% probability of naval confrontation in the Channel area. Offer: if you maintain respect for Dutch-Belgian neutrality and keep your fleet posture defensive, I will not contest Kie-adjacent moves from my coastal armies this turn, allowing a tacit buffer to avoid escalation."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "AUSTRIA",
    "content": "Vienna — your situation in the Balkans looks strained. England cannot help you directly on land, but a stable Balkans reduces pressure on the Mediterranean and keeps my southern sea routes safer. I urge you to avoid hasty southern pushes that might draw Turkey and Russia into wider commitments; such entanglements increase the chance (quantified ~50%) of Russian naval campaigns that could threaten the western Mediterranean. If you can stabilize locally, I will keep my western fleets focused on preventing continental consolidation and can consider limited diversionary actions if you provide reliable coordination."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "RUSSIA",
    "content": "St. Petersburg — a steady Russian front against Turkey keeps the Black Sea contested and diverts Ottoman energy from the wider conflict, which benefits British maritime security. England will not seek confrontation with you so long as our naval lanes remain free and you avoid sudden northern fleet moves toward Scandinavia that risk collisions with my Norwegian and Swedish holdings. Note: forecasting shows France likely-to-aggress (60%); if France destabilizes the west, I may be forced to redeploy efforts toward the Channel which would reduce attention on northern waters. Please coordinate if you plan moves near STP/FIN so we avoid accidental naval clashes."
  }
]

